# Project Workflow

- Treat this as a long-term open-source browser game foundation, not a throwaway prototype.
- Use the autonomy model in `docs/AgentOperatingModel.md`: proceed independently on scoped, low-risk work that follows the approved architecture.
- For routine implementation, briefly state the plan and proceed. For architectural work, ambiguous requirements, broad refactors, major dependencies, or scope changes, explain tradeoffs and wait for approval.
- Challenge requests that would create tight coupling, god classes, hidden global state, or renderer-owned gameplay.
- Keep combat out of the MVP unless the project vision changes explicitly.
- Prefer TypeScript, Vite, Babylon.js, Vitest, and Howler.js unless an approved ADR changes the stack.
- Update tests and documentation with substantive feature work.
- Agents may make coherent Conventional Commits for completed units of work, but should not push or perform destructive git operations without explicit approval.
- Record major architectural decisions in `docs/DecisionLog.md`; use ADRs for decisions that matter to contributors.
